Tyrone DeSilva

Outline¶

Along the way we'll learn about how pandas and statsmodels are useful tools for handling data.

Time Series¶

  • Collection of random variables indexed over time(stochastic process)
  • Discrete time(fixed interval)
    • E.g. 1/day, 1/month, 1/quarter
  • Time domain
  • Examples:
    • NYSE
    • Temperature
    • Sound wave

Moving Average¶

Moving average involves taking the average of a rolling window of observations. Generally moving average is useful for looking at trend. Looks something like this for odd $w$: $$ \hat{y_i} = \frac{1}{w}\sum_{j=i - \frac{w - 1}{2}}^{i + \frac{w - 1}{2}}{y_j} $$

Enlarging the window smooths out the moving average.

In [83]:
# 28 day moving average window
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

fig.set_size_inches(20, 10)
ax.plot(btc_df.index, btc_df["Close"].rolling(28).mean(), label="28 day")
ax.plot(btc_df.index, btc_df["Close"].rolling(60).mean(), label="60 day")
ax.plot(btc_df.index, btc_df["Close"].rolling(180).mean(), label="180 day")
ax.plot(btc_df.index, btc_df["Close"].rolling(365).mean(), label="365 day")
ax.legend()

Seasonality¶

  • dummy variables for each $i = 1...k$ for period $k$
  • e.g. dummy variable for each day of the week when the interval is one week
In [64]:
# de-seasonalize data
# first remove the trend using moving average
moving_average = btc_df.index, btc_df["Close"].rolling(60).mean()
detrended_close = btc_df.Close - moving_average[1]
day_of_week_list = ["monday", "tuesday", "wednesday", "thursday", "friday", "saturday", "sunday"]
days_df = pd.DataFrame({"close": detrended_close,
                        "day": detrended_close.index.map(lambda x: day_of_week_list[x.dayofweek])})
days_df["day"] = days_df["day"].astype("category")
days_df_dummied = pd.get_dummies(days_df)
days_df_dummied.dropna(inplace=True)

x = days_df_dummied.drop(columns="close").values
y = days_df_dummied.close.values

lr = LinearRegression()
lr.fit(x, y)
pred = lr.predict(x)
In [90]:
# BTC Price by DoW

Residual¶

Residual is the leftover after seasonality and trend has been removed. Ideally residual should look like gaussian noise.

In [66]:
rolling_average = btc_df["Close"].rolling(60).mean()

days_df = pd.DataFrame({"close": btc_df.Close - rolling_average,
                        "day": btc_df.index.map(lambda x: day_of_week_list[x.dayofweek])})

days_df["day"] = days_df["day"].astype("category")
days_df_dummied = pd.get_dummies(days_df)
days_df_dummied.dropna(inplace=True)

x = days_df_dummied.drop(columns="close").values
y = days_df_dummied.close.values

lr = LinearRegression()
lr.fit(x, y)

pred = lr.predict(x)

residual = btc_df.Close[-pred.shape[0]:] - pred - rolling_average[-pred.shape[0]:]

Stationarity¶

A time series $\{x_{t_1}, x_{t_2}, ..., x_{t_k}\}$ is said to be stationary if $$ P(x_{t_1} \leq c_1, x_{t_2} \leq c_2, ..., x_{t_k} \leq c_k) = P(x_{t_1 + h} \leq c_1, x_{t_2 + h} \leq c_2, ..., x_{t_k + h} \leq c_k); \forall h \in \mathbb{Z} $$

  • no trend, seasonality, periodicity, etc.
  • Dickey-Fuller test for stationarity
    • p-value refers to probability of getting data as uncorrelated as the sample given the time series is not stationary

Quick Intro to Hypothesis Testing¶

  • frequentist statistics
  • $H_0$: Data is not stationary
  • $H_A$: Data is stationary.
  • calculate the probability of getting the data, assuming the null hypothesis
  • if $p \lt \alpha$, reject $H_0$
In [68]:
# Dickey-Fuller test for stationarity on BTC data
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller

test_fields = ['Test Statistic','p-value','#Lags','Number of Observations Used']

test_results = adfuller(btc_df["Close"])

for field, result in zip(test_fields, test_results[:4]):
    print(f"{field}: {result}")

for key, value in test_results[4].items():
    print(f"Critical value ({key}): {value}")

Autocorrelation¶

Autocorrelation looks at the correlation between the values of the exogenous variable at various time lags. The x-axis is the time lag, and the y-axis the correlation for points at that time lag. If we assume our time series is stationary, autocorrelations should only depend on the time lag, i.e. $Cor(x_{t_k}, x_{t_k + h}$ is independent of $t_k$.

In [69]:
from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf
import numpy as np

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
fig.set_size_inches((20, 10))

plot_acf(btc_df.Close, lags=np.arange(0, 30), ax=ax)
None

Partial Autocorrelation¶

Partial autocorrelation corrects for correlations between smaller time lags when calculating the autocorrelation for a given time lag.

Differencing¶

The most simple way of making a time series stationary is differencing. First difference is calculated as: $$ y_2 - y_1, y_3 - y_2, .., y_n - y_{n - 1} $$

ARIMA model¶

  • Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average
  • makes non-stationary data stationary

ARIMA models have two components.

Autoregression¶

  • infinite impulse response
  • if series is stationary, effect of $\epsilon_k$ tends to 0 as $i \rightarrow 0$
  • regression on previous values of endogeneous variable $$ X_t = c + \sum_{i=1}^{p}{\varphi_i X_{t - i}} + \epsilon_t $$

Moving Average¶

  • finite impulse response
  • regression on previous values of the error term $$ X_t = \mu + \epsilon_t + \sum_{i=1}^{q}{\theta_i \epsilon_{t -i}}$$

Integrated¶

  • make data stationary via differencing
  • fit ARMA model on differences
  • integrate differences to get forecasts
In [75]:
from statsmodels.tsa.arima_model import ARIMA

btc_log = btc_df.Close.map(np.log)

btc_model = ARIMA(btc_log, order=(10, 1, 2)).fit()  # parameters: p, d, q

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
fig.set_size_inches((20, 10))
plot_acf(btc_log.diff().iloc[1:], lags=np.arange(0, 30), ax=ax)
